            <div type="commentary">
                <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1">
                        <p>It is impossible to recreate the first line of the Roman-letter inscription '[...]CIVS' as this is a very common name-ending. There are also a number of possible suggestions for the last name, including <hi rend="italic"> Maurianus, Taurioanus, Scaurianus, Gaurianus </hi>and <hi rend="italic"> Laurianus</hi>.Thus, the recreation of the inscription for translation to English is subject to debate. The Welsh corpus elaborates on the dating of the inscription in noting <q>that, with its arrangement in short horizontal lines, the medial stop after the S in the second line and the purely Latin character of its word-endings, this inscription appears to [be] sub-Roman rather than 'Early Christian' in character</q> <bibl><ptr target="RED2007"/>Redknap and Lewis 2007<citedRange unit="page"> 231-3</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
                    </item>
                <item n="2">
                    <p>The Ogham inscription is remarkable in being the only known example of an Ogham inscription overlying a Latin one. It is further notable in that the two inscriptions do not appear to be related. The word in the inscription, TARICORO, is obscure but likely Irish. <bibl><ptr target="THO1994"/>Thomas</bibl> compares TARICORO with OI <hi rend="italic"> Tairmesc</hi> in which <hi rend="italic">Tair-</hi> is prepositional. The Welsh Corpus notes that <q>a possible second element is <hi rend="italic">*kor-,</hi> 'cast, throw' (Old Irish <hi rend="italic">cuir-</hi></q>.<bibl><ptr target="RED2007"/>Redknap and Lewis 2007 <citedRange unit="page">231-3</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
                </item> 
                    </list>
